                            <comment id="15745437" author="carlyeks" created="Tue, 13 Dec 2016 15:38:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Code looks good, and I think I understand why we can&apos;t use the &lt;tt&gt;ClientState&lt;/tt&gt;, but just to make sure: it&apos;s because of the way we share the permissions statements between resources.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That is, if we had a &lt;tt&gt;GrantFunctionPermissionsStatement&lt;/tt&gt;, we could add a new interface &lt;tt&gt;KeyspacedStatement&lt;/tt&gt; (or something) which would use the &lt;tt&gt;ClientState&lt;/tt&gt; as in &lt;tt&gt;CFStatement&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15836364" author="beobal" created="Tue, 24 Jan 2017 18:01:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the review. Yes, you&apos;re right that the current class hierarchy for authz statements is somewhat limiting here. Because &lt;tt&gt;PermissionsManagementStatement&lt;/tt&gt; takes a &lt;tt&gt;IResource&lt;/tt&gt; instance, function names currently have to be fully resolved, which requires the keyspace to resolve arg types. It&apos;d be good to rework that hierarchy but this patch improves things sfor the client slightly.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve committed to 3.0 in &lt;tt&gt;4bbf99372e677979c46de432d3b849895fb433ee&lt;/tt&gt; and merged to 3.11 and trunk.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
